# JewelTime UI - Project Rules & Context

## Project Overview
JewelTime UI is an e-commerce jewelry store website. It consists of:
- **Static HTML pages** - Marketing/brochure pages (home, about, blog, shop, cart, checkout, etc.)
- **SCSS/CSS** - Custom styles with Bootstrap integration
- **Vue 3 App** - Full-featured SPA for the storefront (Vue 3 + Vite + Pinia + Vue Router + Bootstrap 5)
- **Express.js Server** - Backend API with routes for auth, orders, wishlist, coupons, locations, policies, shipping addresses

---

## Project Structure

### Root Level
- `home.html`, `about-us.html`, `blog-grid.html`, `blog-single.html` - Static marketing pages
- `cart-page.html`, `checkout-page.html` - Static cart/checkout pages
- `shop-right-sidebar.html`, `shop-accordion.html` - Static product listing pages
- `contact-us.html`, `faq.html` - Static info pages
- `style.css` - Compiled stylesheet
- `css/` - Vendor CSS (bootstrap, plugins, colors, responsive)
- `js/` - Frontend JavaScript (bootstrap, custom, popper)
- `scss/` - SCSS source files (base, responsive, custom variables)
- `fonts/` - Custom fonts (Jost family, icomoon icons)
- `images/` - Image assets

### `server/` - Express.js Backend (Legacy)
- `index.js` - Server entry point (legacy, used for local dev)
- `routes/` - API route handlers (legacy)
- `.env` - Environment variables

### ERP Backend (Primary) - `http://localhost:8081`
- **Auth**: POST `/api/v1/auth/login`, `/api/v1/auth/register`, `/api/v1/auth/refresh-token`
- **Products**: GET/POST `/api/v1/products`, `/api/v1/products/{id}`, `/api/v1/products/search`, `/api/v1/products/category/{categoryId}`
- **Categories**: GET/POST `/api/v1/categories`, `/api/v1/categories/root`, `/api/v1/categories/{id}/subcategories`, `/api/v1/categories/{id}/all-subcategories`
- **Orders**: GET/POST `/api/v1/orders`, `/api/v1/orders/{id}`, `/api/v1/orders/user/{userId}`, `/api/v1/orders/{id}/status`
- **Users**: GET `/api/v1/users`, `/api/v1/users/{id}`, `/api/v1/users/email/{email}`
- **Partners/Suppliers**: GET/POST `/api/v1/partners`, `/api/v1/partners/{id}`, `/api/v1/partners/type/{type}`
- **Inventory**: POST `/api/v1/inventory/create`, `/api/v1/inventory/add-stock`, `/api/v1/inventory/reduce-stock`, `/api/v1/inventory/adjust-stock`, `/api/v1/inventory/transfer-stock`
- **Payments**: GET/POST `/api/v1/payments`, `/api/v1/payments/{id}`
- **Notifications**: GET/POST `/api/v1/notifications`

### `vue-app/` - Vue 3 Frontend Application
- **Tech Stack**: Vue 3 (Composition API) + Vite + Pinia + Vue Router + Bootstrap 5 + Axios
- `src/App.vue` - Root component
- `src/main.js` - App entry point
- `src/router/index.js` - Vue Router configuration
- `src/pages/` - Page components
  - `Cart.vue`, `Checkout.vue`, `ProductDetail.vue`
  - `SignIn.vue`, `Register.vue`, `Profile.vue`, `Dashboard.vue`
  - `Wishlist.vue`, `PolicyPage.vue`
- `src/components/` - Reusable components
  - `Header.vue`, `Footer.vue`, `ProductCard.vue`
  - `CookieConsent.vue`, `Captcha.vue`
- `src/stores/` - Pinia stores
  - `locationStore.js`, `wishlistStore.js`
- `src/assets/` - Static assets

---

## Coding Conventions

### General
- Use **English** for all code, comments, commit messages, and documentation
- Follow **semantic HTML5** for static pages
- Use **BEM-like** or descriptive CSS class naming (e.g., `.col-12`, `.header`, `.footer`)
- Responsive design via Bootstrap grid and custom media queries

### Vue App
- Use **Vue 3 Composition API** with `<script setup>` syntax
- State management via **Pinia stores**
- Routing via **Vue Router** with lazy-loaded routes
- HTTP requests via **Axios**
- Bootstrap 5 for UI components and layout
- Components follow PascalCase naming (e.g., `ProductCard.vue`, `CookieConsent.vue`)
- Store files follow camelCase naming (e.g., `locationStore.js`, `wishlistStore.js`)

### Server (Express.js)
- RESTful API routes
- Environment variables via `.env` file (`dotenv` package)
- Route handlers organized by domain (`routes/` directory)
- Business logic in `services/` directory
- CORS enabled for cross-origin requests
- Error handling via try/catch with proper HTTP status codes

### SCSS/CSS
- Custom SCSS in `scss/` directory
- Variables in `_customVariables.scss`
- Bootstrap overrides and custom animations
- Compiled output to `style.css` and `css/` directory

### Package Management
- Root `package.json` - Server dependencies (root level)
- `server/package.json` - Server dependencies
- `vue-app/package.json` - Vue app dependencies
- Use `npm` for package management

---

## Commit Message Guidelines

### Format
```
<type>(<scope>): <short summary>

[optional body]
```

### Types
- **feat** - New feature
- **fix** - Bug fix
- **refactor** - Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
- **style** - Changes that do not affect the meaning of the code (formatting, etc.)
- **docs** - Documentation only changes
- **perf** - Performance improvement
- **test** - Adding or correcting tests
- **chore** - Changes to build process, tools, or dependencies
- **revert** - Reverts a previous commit

### Scopes
- **server** - Backend API changes
- **vue-app** - Vue frontend changes
- **static** - Static HTML/CSS pages
- **scss** - SCSS/CSS style changes
- **config** - Configuration files
- **docs** - Documentation
- **deps** - Dependency updates

### Examples
```
feat(vue-app): add product filtering by category
fix(server): handle empty cart checkout error
refactor(static): consolidate header navigation into reusable include
style(scss): update brand color variables to match logo
chore(deps): upgrade axios to v1.17
docs: update README with setup instructions
```

### Best Practices
- Use **imperative mood** ("add" not "added" or "adds")
- **Capitalize** the first word after the type/scope
- Keep the summary line under **72 characters**
- Reference **issue/PR numbers** in the body when applicable
- Separate subject from body with a **blank line**
- Explain **what** and **why**, not **how**

---

## Task Execution Steps
1. Understand which part of the project is being modified (server, vue-app, static, config)
2. Read relevant files to understand existing conventions
3. Make focused, incremental changes
4. Test changes when applicable
5. Use appropriate linting/formatting for the file type
6. Commit with a descriptive, conventional commit message